g%20the%20woody%20trunks%20of%20trees%2C%20rotting%20them%20away%20and%20thus%20curtailing%20newer%20formations%20of%20coal.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20while%20dinosaurs%20still%20tromped%20happily%20across%20insular%20India%2C%20volcanoes%20began%20to%20belch%20as%20the%20Indian%20plate%20crossed%20over%20%E2%80%98hot%20spots%E2%80%99%20in%20the%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20mantle.%20But%20following%20the%20impact%20of%20the%20Chicxulub%20meteor%20on%20the%20opposite%20side%20of%20the%20globe%2C%20those%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.smithsonianmag.com%2Fscience-nature%2Fmeteorite-killed-dinosaurs-also-triggered-underwater-volcanoes-180968106%2F%5C%22%3Evolcanoes%20boomed%20into%20overdrive%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20burying%20most%20of%20the%20island%20in%20lava%20and%20spewing%20massive%20quantities%20of%20gas%20into%20the%20atmosphere%20over%20the%20next%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.science.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1126%2Fscience.aac7549%5C%22%3Ehalf%20a%20million%3C%2Fa%3E%20This%20extreme%2C%20prolonged%20environmental%20disruption%20likely%20compounded%20and%20extended%20the%20extinction%20event%20triggered%20by%20the%20meteor%20strike.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%2C%20reptiles%20had%20grown%20gigantic.%20Dinosaurs%2C%20in%20their%20various%20forms%2C%20great%20and%20small%2C%20remained%20the%20dominant%20beasts%20on%20land%20for%20250%20million%20years.%20Their%20heyday%20only%20ended%2C%20one%20fine%20day%20about%2066%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20when%20the%20giant%20Chicxulub%20meteor%20crashed%20into%20the%20sea.%20The%20heat%20of%20the%20collision%20instantly%20incinerated%20large%20swathes%20of%20the%20planet%E2%80%99s%20surface.%20Fire%20and%20rocky%20debris%20rained%20down%20upon%20the%20land.%20The%20impact%20unleashed%20a%20mega-tsunami%20with%20waves%20hundreds%20of%20meters%20high.%20It%20forced%20a%20seismic%20response%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.berkeley.edu%2F2015%2F04%2F30%2Fdid-dinosaur-killing-asteroid-trigger-largest-lava-flows-on-earth%5C%22%3Ecaused%20swarms%20of%20volcanoes%3C%2Fa%3E%20around%20the%20globe%20to%20belch%20and%20spurt%20continuously%20for%20tens%20of%20thousands%20of%20years%2C%20burying%20millions%20of%20kilometres%20of%20land%20under%20burning%20lava%E2%80%94and%20shaping%20the%20geography%20of%20many%20lands%2C%20including%20the%20Deccan%20Plateau.%20This%20magnitude%20of%20devastation%20once%20again%20utterly%20revised%20life%20on%20Earth%2C%20in%20what%E2%80%99s%20referred%20to%20as%20the%20Fifth%20Great%20Mass%20Extinction%20Event%E2%80%94the%20fifth%20time%20that%20most%20species%20then%20existing%20on%20Earth%20rapidly%20died%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20as%20before%2C%20life%20eventually%20bounced%20back%20with%20even%20greater%20diversity.%20New%20mixes%20of%20forests%20grew.%20Birds%20now%20filled%20the%20skies.%20By%20forty%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20mammals%20were%20emerging%20as%20the%20most%20dominant%20class%20of%20creature%20on%20land%2C%20spreading%20themselves%20under%20steamy%20jungle%20canopies%20around%20the%20planet%2C%20some%20even%20sliding%20back%20into%20the%20oceans%2C%20evolving%20into%20whales%20and%20dolphins.%20This%20exuberant%20flowering%20of%20life%20was%20not%20quelled%20even%20as%20the%20planet%20embarked%20upon%20yet%20another%20cooling%20trend.%20Snow%20began%20to%20fall%20again%20after%20many%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20first%20in%20the%20mountains%20of%20Antarctica.%20Over%20the%20following%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20highest%20peaks%2C%20north%20and%20south%2C%20slowly%20donned%20mantles%20of%20ice.%20Earth%20had%20been%20encrusted%20in%20ice%20before%2C%20but%20not%20when%20it%20was%20also%20adorned%20by%20forests%20and%20grasslands%20swarming%20with%20legions%20of%20warm-blooded%20creatures%2C%20birds%20and%20mammals%2C%20amid%20the%20richest%2C%20densest%2C%20most%20diverse%20biota%20it%20had%20ever%20created.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20this%20cooling%2C%20drying%20climate%2C%20some%20forests%20in%20Africa%20were%20burning%20away%20into%20grasslands.%20It%20was%20then%20that%20our%20earliest%20hominid%20ancestors%E2%80%94two-legged%20apes%20of%20short%20stature%E2%80%94climbed%20down%20from%20their%20shrinking%20tree%20cover%20and%20strode%20onto%20the%20African%20savannas%2C%20some%20six%20million%20years%20ago.%20Like%20other%20primates%2C%20they%20probably%20used%20some%20tools%2C%20such%20as%20digging%20sticks.%20But%20over%20the%20next%20few%20million%20years%2C%20as%20their%20cognitive%20capacities%20were%20reshaped%20by%20their%20changing%20environment%2C%20they%20began%20noticing%20the%20properties%20of%20different%20types%20of%20stone%2C%20how%20best%20to%20break%20them%20into%20shapes%20useful%20for%20chopping%20things.%20They%20also%20came%20to%20understand%20some%20things%20about%20fire.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EExtreme%20vulcanism%20across%20insular%20India%20at%20the%20end%20of%20the%20Cretaceous%20Period%20contributed%20to%20the%20mass%20extinction%20event%20that%20ended%20the%20dinosaurs%E2%80%99%20reign.%20The%20resulting%20lava%20beds%20remain%20major%20geologic%20features%20across%20much%20of%20peninsular%20India.%20Today%20called%20the%20Deccan%20Traps%2C%20they%20still%20rank%20among%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpubs.geoscienceworld.org%2Fgsa%2Fgsabulletin%2Farticle-abstract%2F127%2F11-12%2F1507%2F126064%2FTriggering-of-the-largest-Deccan-eruptions-by-the%3FredirectedFrom%3Dfulltext%5C%22%3Emost%20extensive%20and%20voluminous%3C%2Fa%3E%20lava%20fields%20known%20on%20Earth.%20Some%20sixty-six%20million%20years%20later%2C%20people%20would%20carve%20Buddhist%20monasteries%20and%20Hindu%20temples%20into%20their%20cliff%20faces%20at%20Ajanta%20and%20Ellora.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%20two%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20when%20massive%20fields%20of%20ice%20had%20well%20taken%20hold%20of%20Antarctica%20and%20the%20far%20northern%20latitudes%2C%20our%20early%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faustralian.museum%2Flearn%2Fscience%2Fhuman-evolution%2Fhominid-and-hominin-whats-the-difference%2F%5C%22%3Ehominin%3C%2Fa%3E%20ancestor%2C%20%3Cem%3EHomo%20erectus%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20had%20become%20recognisably%20human%2C%20though%20not%20quite%20identical%20to%20us%20(we%2C%20%3Cem%3EHomo%20sapiens%20sapiens%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20appeared%20a%20mere%20three%20hundred%20thousand%20years%20ago).%20With%20their%20well-developed%20stone%20tools%20and%20mastery%20of%20fire%2C%20%3Cem%3EH.%20erectus%3C%2Fem%3E%20ventured%20beyond%20Africa%2C%20eventually%20colonizing%20much%20of%20southern%20Eurasia%20from%20what%20today%20is%20Spain%20to%20India%20to%20China%20and%20the%20farthest%20reaches%20of%20peninsular%20southeast%20Asia%20(which%20would%20later%20become%20the%20islands%20of%20Indonesia).%20None%20of%20what%20followed%20would%20have%20been%20possible%20without%20both%20fire%20and%20a%20propensity%20to%20build%20thick%20social%20worlds%2C%20two%20aspects%20of%20being%20human%20that%20appear%20tightly%20linked%20and%20are%20the%20subject%20of%20the%20next%20essay.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EUsha%20Alexander%20trained%20in%20science%20and%20anthropology.%20After%20working%20for%20years%20in%20Silicon%20Valley%2C%20she%20now%20lives%20in%20Gurugram.%20She%E2%80%99s%20written%20two%20novels%3A%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3EThe%20Legend%20of%20Virinara%3Cem%3E%C2%A0and%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3EOnly%20the%20Eyes%20Are%20Mine%3Cem%3E.%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1707996634000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F15155616%2FPandavFalls06.jpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fa-planetary-perspective%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Earth%20was%20born%20about%20four%20and%20a%20half%20billion%20years%20ago%2C%20alongside%20se